/* History */ Updated for accuracy.  Firstly, provided more detail as to what this girl actually said, because there doesn't seem to be any dispute about that.  Secondly, according to the sources, these comments were not made on social media but while the girl was in her own home.
/* Controversy */ Now it is accepted that the original BBC report was false, it's probably appropriate to change the order in which it is covered so as to give less prominence to it.
/* Controversy */ Significant update

This appears to give undue weight to one particular journalist's views.  At this time, there will be many different journalists commenting on this story at the moment with a variety of perspectives.  Why give weight and prominence to this one, especially when (unlike Simon Jack above) her coverage has not in any way led or defined the story.

/* Controversy */ redrafted because the original text implied that Coutts itself had said it closed the account for this reason.  It hasn't.  As the BBC source itself confirms, Coutts itself has not officially commented.  Thus, I have more accurately stated where this claim comes from.
added bracket

Apparently unsourced.  The main body of the article only identifies three kinds of order: (1) men, (2) women and (3) mixed men and women.  Obviously, if there are specific orders that identify themselves as being for gender-nonconforming people, then the article should reflect that.  However, that currently doesn't seem to be the case.
